Simba TVS, distributors of TVS motorcycles and tricycles, has marked this year’s International Women’s Day by training women riders under their Queen Riders Programme – the company’s flagship CSR initiative. The ceremony was presided by the celebrated muralist and artist and founder of the Five Cowries Initiative, Polly Alakija. It will be recalled that the Queen Riders’ programme was established to teach women from under-represented backgrounds how to safely ride and repair tricycles, enabling them to partake in the industry and increase their families’ disposable incomes. A unique event was held where the women graduates and dignitaries painted the tricycles under the guidance of Polly and her assistants from the Five Cowries Foundation who use art to encourage children to express their creativity while also enabling their education. Mrs Olubunmi Kuforiji, popularly known as Mama Keke, Mrs Olayiwola Gloria of Cedar Microfinance Bank, an institution which helps finance graduates of the program to buy TVS tricycles, as well as representatives of the Simba Group, supported the event. According the company’s spokesperson, Women’s Empowerment is a key focus of the Simba Group and in particular the Queen Rider’s Programme as a key platform for achieving the vision of enriching lives of Nigerians. He said that the programme was born from the Group’s desire to train women from underrepresented backgrounds, so that they have a chance to increase thwweir total family income. The Simba Training School which also conducts advanced mechanic courses, has provided training to these riders, free of charge. He said such trainings are regularly conducted by Simba TVS across the country and several of these Queen Riders are not only driving kekes but also some have become fleet owners operating several tricycles.